name: complexity-taming
description: Manage growing codebase complexity through boundaries, dependency control, and strategic refactoring

# Purpose
Keep your codebase navigable and maintainable as it grows. Establish clear boundaries, control dependencies, and know when to split or merge.

# When to use
Use this skill when:
- "Where does this code go?" becomes hard to answer
- Changes in one area break unrelated features
- New team members struggle to understand the code
- You're afraid to touch certain parts
- Features take longer to implement than expected
- You're planning a refactor

# Inputs
- Current pain points (what feels hard?)
- Codebase structure overview
- Growth trajectory (what's coming next?)
- Team size and experience

# Output Format (required)
1) Complexity diagnosis (where is the pain?)
2) Boundary analysis (current vs ideal)
3) Dependency map (what depends on what?)
4) Refactoring plan (prioritized)
5) Prevention rules (how to stay clean)
6) Verification (how to know it's better)

# Complexity Symptoms

## Code Navigation Issues
| Symptom | Likely Cause |
|---------|--------------|
| Can't find where X happens | Poor module boundaries |
| Same logic in multiple places | Missing shared abstraction |
| Files with 1000+ lines | God objects, no separation |
| Deep folder nesting | Over-engineering |
| Circular imports | Wrong dependency direction |

## Change Impact Issues
| Symptom | Likely Cause |
|---------|--------------|
| Small change breaks many things | Tight coupling |
| Must update 10 files for one feature | Scattered responsibility |
| Tests break constantly | Testing implementation, not behavior |
| Merge conflicts everywhere | Poor ownership boundaries |

## Understanding Issues
| Symptom | Likely Cause |
|---------|--------------|
| Need to read entire codebase | No clear entry points |
| Comments say "don't touch" | Hidden complexity, fear |
| Business logic buried in UI | Layer violations |
| Magic numbers/strings everywhere | Missing domain modeling |

# Module Boundary Design

## Principles
1. **Single Responsibility**: One reason to change
2. **Information Hiding**: Internal details stay internal
3. **Explicit Dependencies**: Import what you need, no globals
4. **Stable Interfaces**: Change internals, not contracts

## Good Boundary Characteristics
- Clear public API (what can others use?)
- Internal implementation hidden
- Dependencies point inward (toward stable core)
- Can be understood without reading internals
- Can be tested in isolation

## Flutter/Dart Module Structure
```
lib/
├── core/                    # Shared utilities, no business logic
│   ├── extensions/
│   ├── constants/
│   └── utils/
├── features/                # Feature modules (vertical slices)
│   ├── auth/
│   │   ├── data/           # Repository implementations, DTOs
│   │   ├── domain/         # Entities, repository interfaces
│   │   └── presentation/   # Widgets, state management
│   ├── profile/
│   └── messaging/
├── shared/                  # Shared widgets, themes
│   ├── widgets/
│   └── theme/
└── main.dart
```

## Feature Module Template
```
feature_name/
├── data/
│   ├── repositories/       # Implementation
│   ├── data_sources/       # Remote/local sources
│   └── models/             # DTOs, JSON serialization
├── domain/
│   ├── entities/           # Core business objects
│   ├── repositories/       # Abstract interfaces
│   └── usecases/           # Business logic (optional)
└── presentation/
    ├── screens/            # Full screens
    ├── widgets/            # Feature-specific widgets
    └── state/              # Riverpod/Bloc/etc
```

# Dependency Management

## Dependency Direction Rules
```
presentation → domain ← data
     ↓            ↑        ↓
   shared      core    external
```

- **Domain depends on nothing** (pure business logic)
- **Presentation depends on domain** (not data)
- **Data depends on domain** (implements interfaces)
- **Never**: presentation → data directly

## Import Rules
```dart
// GOOD: Feature imports from core
import 'package:app/core/utils/date_utils.dart';

// GOOD: Feature imports shared widgets
import 'package:app/shared/widgets/loading.dart';

// BAD: Feature A imports Feature B internals
import 'package:app/features/auth/data/auth_repository_impl.dart';

// GOOD: Feature A imports Feature B's public API
import 'package:app/features/auth/auth.dart'; // barrel file
```

## Detecting Bad Dependencies
- Circular imports (A → B → A)
- Reaching across features (auth → profile/data)
- UI importing data layer directly
- Core depending on features

# State Management Boundaries

## Where State Lives
| State Type | Location | Example |
|------------|----------|---------|
| UI state | Widget/local | Form inputs, animations |
| Feature state | Feature provider | User profile, messages |
| App state | Root provider | Auth status, theme |
| Server state | Cache/repository | API responses |

## Avoid State Sprawl
- One source of truth per data type
- Derive computed state, don't duplicate
- Clear ownership (who updates this?)
- Explicit dependencies between providers

# Refactoring Strategies

## When to Split
- Module has multiple unrelated responsibilities
- Different change frequencies (UI vs logic)
- Different teams need to own parts
- Testing requires too much setup

## When to Merge
- Artificial separation (data + domain too thin)
- Always changed together
- Circular dependencies
- Over-abstraction (interfaces with one implementation)

## Safe Refactoring Steps
1. **Characterization tests**: Capture current behavior
2. **Extract**: Move code to new location, keep old as delegate
3. **Migrate callers**: Update imports one by one
4. **Remove old**: Delete the original once all migrated
5. **Verify**: Run tests, check no regressions

## Strangler Fig Pattern (for large refactors)
1. Build new module alongside old
2. Route new features to new module
3. Gradually migrate existing features
4. Remove old module when empty

# Complexity Prevention Rules

## File Size Limits
- Widget files: < 200 lines
- Logic files: < 300 lines
- If larger, split by responsibility

## Nesting Limits
- Max folder depth: 4 levels
- Max callback nesting: 3 levels
- Max class inheritance: 2 levels (prefer composition)

## Naming Conventions
- Folders: feature or responsibility
- Files: one primary export per file
- Classes: noun describing what it is
- Functions: verb describing what it does

## Code Review Checklist
- [ ] Does this belong in this module?
- [ ] Are dependencies pointing the right direction?
- [ ] Is the public API minimal?
- [ ] Can this be understood without reading everything?
- [ ] Will this be easy to change later?

# Measuring Complexity

## Quantitative Signals
- File count per feature (< 20 ideal)
- Import depth (< 4 hops)
- Cyclomatic complexity (< 10 per function)
- Change coupling (files changed together)

## Qualitative Signals
- Time to find where to make a change
- Confidence when making changes
- Onboarding time for new developers
- Fear factor ("don't touch this")

# Common Patterns to Apply

## Facade Pattern
Hide complex subsystem behind simple interface:
```dart
// Instead of clients knowing all the pieces
class AuthFacade {
  final AuthRepository _repo;
  final TokenStorage _tokens;
  final Analytics _analytics;
  
  Future<User> login(String email, String password) async {
    // Coordinate all the pieces
  }
}
```

## Repository Pattern
Abstract data access:
```dart
abstract class UserRepository {
  Future<User> getById(String id);
  Future<void> save(User user);
}
// Implementation details hidden in data layer
```

## Feature Flags for Migration
```dart
if (FeatureFlags.useNewProfileScreen) {
  return NewProfileScreen();
} else {
  return OldProfileScreen();
}
```

# Anti-Patterns to Avoid

- **God Object**: One class that does everything
- **Shotgun Surgery**: One change requires many file edits
- **Feature Envy**: Code that uses another module's data more than its own
- **Primitive Obsession**: Using strings/ints instead of domain types
- **Speculative Generality**: Abstractions for features that don't exist

# When Things Are Getting Better
- New features require fewer file changes
- Bug fixes are localized
- Onboarding is faster
- Tests are easier to write
- You can explain the architecture in 2 minutes
